<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900907-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>900907-0027.</DOCID><HL>   Charges Are Amended   Against Former Officer   Of Columbia Savings</HL><DATE>09/07/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CSV</CO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)</IN><GV>TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Thrift regulators said they amended civilcharges against Thomas Spiegel, seeking an unspecified amountof additional restitution from the former executive ofColumbia Savings andamp; Loan Association.   The new charges by the Office of Thrift Supervision accuseMr. Spiegel of causing the thrift to incur an additional lossof $29.2 million by building lavish new corporateheadquarters in Beverly Hills, Calif. The building, accordingto the regulators, was built without regard to cost, andincluded a multilevel gymnasium, &quot;survival chamber&quot; bathroomswith bullet-proof glass, and an independent air and foodsupply.</LP><TEXT>   In July, the OTS filed civil charges against Mr. Spiegel,accusing him of using thrift funds for such acquisitions as ahuge gun collection, aircraft and $7,000 in Michael Jacksonconcert tickets. The agency sought $24 million in restitutionand penalties at that time. Mr. Spiegel denied all charges.   Contrary to past practice, the hearing for Mr. Spiegelwill be public, the regulators said, as will anadministrative hearing of civil charges against CharlesKeating, former chairman of the parent of Lincoln Savings andamp;Loan Association, Irvine, Calif. Neither hearing date hasbeen set.</TEXT></DOC>